The '''European Association for the Teaching of Academic Writing''' (EATAW)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eataw.eu/|title=Home|publisher=|accessdate=30 November 2016}}</ref> is an academic association supporting scholarly activity in [[academic writing]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.adm.heacademy.ac.uk/events/the-roles-of-writing-development-in-higher-education-and-beyond2019 |title=The Roles of Writing Development in Higher Education and Beyond’. — ADM-HEA |publisher=Adm.heacademy.ac.uk |date= |accessdate=2012-05-09}}</ref> The association was first established in 1999<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6DZL-NCULn0&list=PL_0phSnA7tyRIMnYmdUbxTMui74LsPcYh|title=CEU's Center for Academic Writing Hosts 7th EATAW Conference|first=|last=Central European University|date=15 July 2013|publisher=|accessdate=30 November 2016|via=YouTube}}</ref> with the first conference being held in 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britishcouncil.org/sr/newsletter-sep-07-elt-flash-eataw-for-the-4th-time-3.doc|title=British Council - Serbia|publisher=|accessdate=30 November 2016}}</ref> The Europe-wide association has three main activities: a bi-annual conference, an Internet forum and ''the Journal of Academic Writing''.<ref name="coventry1">{{cite web|url=http://e-learning.coventry.ac.uk/ojs/index.php/joaw |title=Journal of Academic Writing |publisher=E-learning.coventry.ac.uk |date= |accessdate=2012-05-09}}</ref>
==The EATAW Conference==
The EATAW conference is held every two years in a European University. It was first held in 2001 in Groningen. The occasion of the bi-annual conference is when the EATAW board is elected for a term of two years.<ref>http://www.eataw.eu/eataw-board.html</ref>
